x4freetext: Pd-300 neutron generator
Approximately 10 g of natural isotopic composition
(99.99% pure) was made into a pellet of 0.156 cm
thickness and 2.0 cm diameter. Three such pellets
were prepared. Monitor foils (Nb, 99.99% pure, 0.12
mm thick) of the same diameter as the pellets were
then attached in front and at the back of each sample.
Neutrons were produced by an effective deuteron
beam energy of 134 keV and beam current of 260 uA.
The T-Ti target used in the generator had a thickness
of 2.8 mg/cm2, and the diameter of the active zone
was 1.2 cm.
Gamma-ray activities were determined by a high-
purity germanium detector (ORTEC, model GEM 60P,
crystal diameter: 70.1 mm, crystal length: 72.3 mm,
made in the United States) with a relative efficiency
of about 68% and an energy resolution of 1.69 keV at
1332 keV for Co-60. The efficiency of the detector
was pre-calibrated using various standard gamma
sources, which were Co-57, Co-60, Cd-109, Ba-133,
The Au-Si surface barrier detector used at
135 deg accompanying alpha-particle tube was 110 cm
from the target.
Irradiation of the samples was lasted about 3
to 4 min with a yield around 3 to 4E10 n/(4pi*s) .
The groups of sample were placed at 0, 90 or 135
degree relative to the beam direction and centered
about the T-Ti target at distances of about 40 mm.
During irradiation, the neutron flux was monitored by
accompanying alpha particles so that corrections
could be made for small variations in the yield.
The correction factors for the self-absorption of the
sample at 156.6, 190.3, 511.0, and 1299.8 keV are
Total uncertainty
Counting statistics 1.0-6.8%
Detector efficiency 2-3.0%
Weight of samples 0.1%
Self-absorption of gamma-ray 2%
Cooling and measuring times 0.1-3%
Uncertainties in branching ratio of
the characteristic gamma rays 1.0-8.5%
Uncertainties in the half-lives of
the radioactive product nuclei 0.02-1.4%
Abundance of the target isotope 0.1-
Standard cross sections uncertainties 1.5%
Data were obtained from TABLE 3 and text (p7)
of Nuclear Science and Engineering,188,198,2017
Compiled by Lin Li(CNDC)
Contribution of the 113In(n,2n)112mIn reaction via
isomeric transition (IT) (100%) was subtracted.
